english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Four Excellences
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: "The Pavilion of Four Excellences bears the name that the Venerable Master of Hidden Retirement, Grand Academician of the Hall of Refined Letters, inscribed upon it himself. In his youth, the Master achieved the highest honors in the examinations, ascended to the Jade Hall, entered the Forbidden Ministry, served as overseer of the Cypress Bureau, and as inspector of Ch'ungch'ŏng Province. Wherever he went, he left a mark of distinction. He had already exhausted the positions that ambitious officials covet and had tired of their pursuit. Truly, the Master's official career was magnificent! Yet his heart soared beyond such things, dwelling always in clouds and mountains, in scenes of mist and stone. Moreover, immersed in the learning of principle and the nature of all things in the manner of the philosophers of Lianyuan and Luoyang, he never knew weariness. Thus it is clear that he did not regard fame and fortune as worth a grain in his breast.\n\nSoutheast of the capital, some tens of li distant, stands Mount Toro. There upon its southern slope the Master built a humble dwelling. During his leisure, he would ride forth on horseback to and fro, fulfilling his long-held aspiration. He named the pavilion \"Four Excellences,\" drawing upon the words of Master Cheng: \"The beautiful moods of the four seasons are shared with all people.\" When the Ming emissary, Director of the Imperial Stables Zhu Mengxian, heard of this, he was delighted. He painted the landscape and composed verses for it. The Master commanded me to write this record. But I am shallow in learning and have long been afflicted by illness—how can I presume to write? Yet I cannot refuse the Master's command on grounds of literary inadequacy. \n\nConsider: from the interaction of yin and yang arise water, fire, wood, metal, and earth. The qi of the five phases flows in harmonious order, and the four seasons proceed in their course. Thus ten thousand things attain their growth. The spirit of the five phases, bestowed upon humans, manifests as the five virtues—humanity, righteousness, propriety, wisdom, and trustworthiness. When the nature of these five constants is expressed, the four sentiments arise. Thus all affairs achieve their completion. In heaven these appear as the four seasons; in humanity as the four sentiments. Their underlying principle is one and the same.\n\nYet the multitude of people—their nature is constrained by material composition, obscured by desires for things. They engage in endless calculations of gain and loss, fame and profit, a hundred schemes and a thousand compromises. Within their hearts, ice and fire wage perpetual war. How then can one speak of preserving and nurturing the five virtues and four sentiments? The morning fades into evening, cold yields to heat—these transformations pass unobserved. How much less can one hope to achieve resonance with the beautiful moods of the four seasons? Few are those who escape such bondage.\n\nBut the Master has already freed himself from the entanglements of material desire and worldly acclaim. His cultivation through study and self-reflection advances daily toward ever greater clarity. His five virtues and four sentiments thus emerge with irresistible force, moving in silent accord with the unstoppable flow of the five phases and four seasons. How could there be any separation between them, any distinction of above and below, self and other? Between heaven and earth beats one great pulse. The same heart dwells within his breast. Though the four seasons turn and fade, their beauty remains ever-present. The joy he experiences transcends all words and description. This, I believe, is why he drew upon what lies closest at hand to name his pavilion.\n\nThe qi of the four seasons fills heaven and earth—can any thing be omitted? The movement of the four seasons penetrates all time—can any moment stand still? The Master's mind transcends the realm of form, pure amid the hidden and manifest. How could his mind and the movement of the four seasons be fundamentally two? Is it not clear, then, that his naming the pavilion \"Four Excellences\" is no mere chance? To transcend the realm of form and remain pure amid the hidden and manifest—this is Heaven's Virtue. With such virtue, one may discourse on the Way of Kings. Should he subsequently rise to the highest offices and bear the responsibility of illuminating the Kingly Way and harmonizing the original forces of heaven and earth, the subtle transformations of his spirit would flow together with heaven and earth and the four seasons, bringing all things to their proper places.\n\nAlas, how profound! Only those who know the Way can truly participate in such things.\n\nWhen spring arrives with warmth, one seeks out flowers and willows. When autumn's shadow rests upon the river, one walks with friends, wine-cup in hand. When summer's rays melt metal and stream downward, one rests in the shade of great trees to enjoy cool breezes. When bitter winter binds all things in frost, one sits by a bright window warmed by the morning sun. Though the four seasons present ever-changing scenes, the joy they kindle knows no end. Even one such as myself partakes of this delight. I have long taken pleasure in these things and chose spring alone to name my humble pavilion. \n\nShould Heaven's fortune grant that I might settle as a neighbor near the Master's Four Excellences, daily supporting myself with staff and cane to follow in his company, observing the transformations of the seasons unfold—this would be the height of blessing for my remaining years.\n\nSomeone said to me: \"The Master's naming of the pavilion carries great meaning, suffusing the six directions and extending through ten thousand eons. But your explanation is narrow and constrained. Moreover, you named your pavilion merely 'Spring'—a grievous partiality. How can you speak truly of the beautiful moods of the four seasons?\" \n\nI replied: \"What fills heaven and earth contains within itself the six directions. What penetrates ancient and modern times contains within itself ten thousand eons. Heaven, earth, and the four seasons share one qi with myself. Since heaven itself manifests as four seasons and spring encompasses all of them, do I not glimpse at least some measure of the boundary of the meaning you speak of?\"\n\nThus I write this record."
  footnotes:
    - Lianyuan and Luoyang refer to the Neo-Confucian philosophers Zhou Dunyi of Lianyuan and the Cheng brothers of Luoyang, whose teachings on principle and human nature profoundly influenced Korean thought.
    - The "four sentiments" (仁義禮智) correspond to the four seasons and represent the proper emotional responses that emerge when human nature is cultivated and undistorted by material desires.
    - Master Cheng (程子) likely refers to Cheng Yi or Cheng Hao, whose insight that the beautiful moods of the seasons are naturally shared with those of cultivated spirit forms the philosophical foundation for the pavilion's name.
